Westerlund (2007) error-correction–based panel cointegration test (WECPT) was employed to inspect the dynamic cointegration connection between EC, FDI, GDP, POP, HEEXP, and CO2e. This test deals with the problem of common factor restriction (Nathaniel et al. 2021d). Westerlund (2007) proposed four cointegration tests to examine the presence of long-run cointegration in the panel data. These tests are based on the error-correction (EC) model and offer three distinct advantages: (1) allow unbalanced panels and unequal series length in units; (2) test heterogeneity that is permitted in the short- and long-run parameters of the error-correction model; and (3) obtain critical value using the bootstrap approach, if a correlation probability exits among units. The WECPT involves the following hypothesis:
